# Design: ClaimInvite Idempotent â€” No Role Downgrade

## Technical Approach

Keep the fix in the service layer. `WorkspaceService.ClaimInvite` will load the invite inside the existing transaction, check whether the user already has a membership in that workspace, and only call `CreateMembership(..., RoleViewer)` for truly new members. Existing members return their current membership unchanged. Invite use count still increments in both paths so a successful claim always consumes one use.

## Architecture Decisions

| Decision | Options | Choice | Rationale |
|---|---|---|---|
| Guard location | Service-layer pre-check; SQL upsert change | Service-layer pre-check | Preserves store contract, keeps business rule visible, matches project standard: business rules stay in service unless persistence contract must change globally. |
| Existing member role | Reapply viewer; preserve current role | Preserve current role | Avoids silent admin/CM downgrade and keeps `ClaimInvite` idempotent for members already in the workspace. |
| Invite consumption | Increment only for new members; increment for every successful claim | Increment for every successful claim | Proposal scope already treats an authenticated successful claim as legitimate usage; skipping increment would allow replay without consuming capacity. |
| Test seam | Only HTTP mock test; SQL test; service helper test | Add focused service-layer test seam | Current phase4 invite route is mocked and cannot prove the regression. A focused service helper test verifies the real rule with low cost. |

